## Cap-helper encapsulation honest

`cost_caps.ts:CapCheckResult = { crossed: boolean, running_total: number | null }`:
- When `cap === undefined` → returns `{ crossed: false, running_total: null }` (no aggregation work)
- When cap configured but not crossed → returns `running_total: number`
- When cap crossed → emits `cost.cap_crossed` event THEN (for day-cap) calls `recordDayCapBlock` THEN returns `{ crossed: true, running_total: number }`

Consumer guards (`crossed && running_total !== null`) defensively reject null rather than coercing to 0 — no-facade pattern per CLAUDE.md §3.

## try/finally bracket complete

`priorRunId` captured at index.ts:207. `try` at :218, `catch` at :516, `finally` at :541. Every return path (success, top-level via `failTopLevel`, cap-crossed early returns, exception rethrow) hits the finally. Day-cap pre-flight at :185-198 is intentionally OUTSIDE the try (env not yet set there).

## Strongest parts (independent assessment)

1. Cap-helper encapsulation makes "we crossed cap N" a single atomic transaction (event-emit + day-cap block-write all inside the helper). Caller knowledge actually decreases.
2. The `running_total: number | null` discriminator preserves the original "no aggregation when no cap" semantics honestly — exactly the no-facade pattern §3 requires.

